{"parentUuid":"8bb5cfe9-438d-423d-8299-73af08bb39d6","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"1a20bc46-b7aa-4307-befd-6752c330b06a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"1. The tool list should come from our dotfiles repo, thats where this is all going to live. If i get another machine, im gonig to download the dotfiles, to install programs, add config files, and backup data etc. Dotfiles repo is the core of how i work on machines. So we should maybe have ~/.dotifles/installer etc. \n\n2. yeah, i think we mentioned this in the .md file, modular checking system, so it iterates over predefined modules, and generates an object stored list with instructinos on how to store. So apt, should save a list of apt based programs, and when installer->install(apt) runs, it grabs the apt programs. This way we can easily add in flatpak whent he day comes around that we fancy using that. Also in order to add a program to the list, all we need todo is all a program to a specific list. E.g. add jagex launcher to the flatpak list. then run install.sh and it will grab it from the list.\nDifferent branches on different machines can of course havea  slightly altered list, rebased off the main list. \n\n3. hmmmm good question, its kinda a mix of all of them... the install should be in scripts, but the file (json?) should be stored in ~/.dotfiles/programs/program_list? Somthing like that?"},"uuid":"34bdc7eb-d84b-440c-8173-506e0e75001d","timestamp":"2026-04-01T08:40:24.368Z","permissionMode":"default","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/sudo-haggis/workshop/backup_scripts","sessionId":"dd1e1896-dd31-4a3f-bd5e-5575827249af","version":"2.1.89","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
{"parentUuid":"34bdc7eb-d84b-440c-8173-506e0e75001d","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MVPpenhHmUnXPLnMsukmNh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1460,"cache_read_input_tokens":18239,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1460},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZckYJrr9uW78bB3DFfsN","type":"assistant","uuid":"a4125860-b8d5-4223-bac5-3ed883dc2d59","timestamp":"2026-04-01T08:40:41.994Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/sudo-haggis/workshop/backup_scripts","sessionId":"dd1e1896-dd31-4a3f-bd5e-5575827249af","version":"2.1.89","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
{"parentUuid":"a4125860-b8d5-4223-bac5-3ed883dc2d59","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MVPpenhHmUnXPLnMsukmNh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good, the picture is clear now. Let me sketch the full structure before we write a line of code.\n\n---\n\n**Proposed repo layout:**\n\n```\n~/.dotfiles/\n├── programs/\n│   ├── apt.txt          # one package per line\n│   ├── snap.txt\n│   ├── flatpak.txt\n│   └── manual.json      # structured: name, check_cmd, install_cmd\n├── scripts/\n│   ├── install.sh       # entry point — iterates modules\n│   ├── startup_check.sh # the MOTD/startup display\n│   └── modules/\n│       ├── apt.sh\n│       ├── snap.sh\n│       ├── flatpak.sh\n│       └── manual.sh\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why plain `.txt` for apt/snap/flatpak, JSON only for manual:**\n\nBash doesn't parse JSON natively — you'd need `jq`. For simple package lists, one-package-per-line `.txt` files are trivially easy to read, diff, and edit. Manual installs genuinely need structure (you need a check command *and* an install command), so JSON with `jq` is justified there.\n\n---\n\n**`manual.json` would look like:**\n\n```json\n[\n  {\n    \"name\": \"claude-code\",\n    \"check\": \"claude\",\n    \"install\": \"npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"jagex-launcher\",\n    \"check\": \"jagex-launcher\",\n    \"install\": \"flatpak install flathub com.jagex.Launcher\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\n---\n\n**Flow:**\n\n```\ninstall.sh\n  └── for each module in [apt, snap, flatpak, manual]:\n        source scripts/modules/<module>.sh\n        install_<module>   # reads programs/<module>.txt or .json\n                           # checks what's missing\n                           # installs, logs failures to failed_<module>.txt\n```\n\n```\nstartup_check.sh\n  └── same module reads, but check-only (no install)\n      → builds \"missing\" list\n      → displays MOTD\n      → if [i] pressed → fzf multi-select from missing list → install selected\n```\n\n---\n\nDoes this structure look right to you? Confirm and I'll propose the actual files we need to create, then we build one at a time."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1460,"cache_read_input_tokens":18239,"output_tokens":1318,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1460,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZckYJrr9uW78bB3DFfsN","type":"assistant","uuid":"c6fd873c-0ab0-419f-94ac-573c17faf240","timestamp":"2026-04-01T08:40:51.636Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/sudo-haggis/workshop/backup_scripts","sessionId":"dd1e1896-dd31-4a3f-bd5e-5575827249af","version":"2.1.89","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
